1
00:00:08,064 --> 00:00:10,006
Hi everybody, my name is Brenda Romero

2
00:00:10,066 --> 00:00:12,548
and this is my talk called Hidden Histories.

3
00:00:13,749 --> 00:00:15,951
So I'm gonna tell you five stories.

4
00:00:16,512 --> 00:00:18,513
And for me, these were stories of discovery

5
00:00:18,794 --> 00:00:20,916
and something that fundamentally changed

6
00:00:20,956 --> 00:00:23,017
how I see the role of women in this industry

7
00:00:23,518 --> 00:00:24,979
and the broader tech community.

8
00:00:25,800 --> 00:00:28,843
So the first story is called Usual Suspects.

9
00:00:29,143 --> 00:00:33,707
and when we're talking about the role of women in tech, we will often bring out what I refer to

10
00:00:33,787 --> 00:00:38,771
as the usual suspects, and we already know who these are. They are, of course, Ada Lovelace.

11
00:00:39,232 --> 00:00:46,018
So she invents the very idea of code in 1843. And then we have Grace Hopper, who invented COBOL,

12
00:00:46,458 --> 00:00:48,640
and she also coined the term compiler.

13
00:00:49,710 --> 00:00:54,095
So she also coined the first computer bug, quite literally.

14
00:00:54,195 --> 00:00:55,857
We're looking at that bug here.

15
00:00:56,878 --> 00:00:59,360
And we also often talk about Hedy Lamarr.

16
00:00:59,480 --> 00:01:01,502
So Hedy Lamarr creates Wi-Fi.

17
00:01:02,663 --> 00:01:05,506
And these women are absolutely, don't get me wrong,

18
00:01:05,546 --> 00:01:07,648
they are absolutely worthy of celebration

19
00:01:07,748 --> 00:01:10,111
and their contributions to code and technology

20
00:01:10,571 --> 00:01:12,333
obviously cannot be understated.

21
00:01:13,463 --> 00:01:20,050
However, I often find in articles talking about tech or women in games that are attempting

22
00:01:20,090 --> 00:01:24,455
to be inclusive, it's the same one or two or three people that are mentioned as if that's

23
00:01:24,695 --> 00:01:25,296
all there were.

24
00:01:25,876 --> 00:01:31,102
When, in reality, if I said, let's talk about men in tech and important male figures in

25
00:01:31,142 --> 00:01:31,343
tech.

26
00:01:31,723 --> 00:01:34,223
we could fill this page and several more pages.

27
00:01:35,044 --> 00:01:37,764
And the reason that I think this is important,

28
00:01:38,124 --> 00:01:41,225
critically important, is because they form the stereotypes

29
00:01:41,545 --> 00:01:43,085
of what we see in our heads,

30
00:01:43,125 --> 00:01:44,426
what everyone sees in their heads

31
00:01:44,446 --> 00:01:46,866
when they think of what that person is.

32
00:01:47,386 --> 00:01:50,647
And they shape the opinions about what people want to become.

33
00:01:50,827 --> 00:01:53,268
So, for instance, what is a surgeon?

34
00:01:53,708 --> 00:01:55,068
And what is a teacher?

35
00:01:57,129 --> 00:01:57,849
What's a nurse?

36
00:02:00,029 --> 00:02:01,370
What's a CEO?

37
00:02:02,928 --> 00:02:09,772
what's a lead programmer? And I saw this take place in my own home when I was going to this

38
00:02:09,892 --> 00:02:14,735
kids coding event. And my daughter, like, mind you, this is my daughter, right? And she says to

39
00:02:14,776 --> 00:02:20,139
me, it's all going to be boys. And she didn't want to go. And so, you can see, like, in her head,

40
00:02:20,319 --> 00:02:24,262
the whole place was just filled with a bunch of little boys. And the reality was that wasn't even

41
00:02:24,362 --> 00:02:30,726
true. It was an event called Coder Dojos, the greatest projects that happens in Dublin.

42
00:02:31,266 --> 00:02:33,148
And there were tons of girls there.

43
00:02:33,228 --> 00:02:35,430
So in fact, I would say to me, it

44
00:02:35,470 --> 00:02:37,392
looked like there were overwhelmingly girls there.

45
00:02:37,512 --> 00:02:40,514
So these ideas, these perceptions,

46
00:02:40,715 --> 00:02:42,797
shape people's opinions.

47
00:02:42,817 --> 00:02:45,299
So usual suspects is what most people know.

48
00:02:45,639 --> 00:02:48,502
And they make career decisions based on those things.

49
00:02:49,391 --> 00:02:55,296
My next story is called impetus. So first I'll tell you a little bit about me and what got me

50
00:02:55,356 --> 00:03:00,701
into the industry and what got me into this in the first place. So I get my start when I'm five,

51
00:03:00,781 --> 00:03:05,826
that's that's when I start making games. And I grew up in northern New York and my family

52
00:03:05,866 --> 00:03:08,908
had little money and so my mother would take me to yard sales.

53
00:03:09,692 --> 00:03:15,695
and I would go around the place and she would give me often a dime and with that dime I could

54
00:03:15,735 --> 00:03:20,899
buy whatever I wanted. So I would usually buy games. Most of the times those games were missing

55
00:03:20,939 --> 00:03:26,722
pieces. So I would gather them all up and I would make my own games and absolutely loved that.

56
00:03:27,443 --> 00:03:31,285
And it really led to a lifelong passion and fascination with games.

57
00:03:31,865 --> 00:03:37,229
When I'm 11, my mother gets me the most amazing thing in the universe. She gets me Dungeons and

58
00:03:37,270 --> 00:03:43,094
Dragons. And it is impossible to understate the love affair that I had with this game.

59
00:03:44,055 --> 00:03:50,299
I could create worlds and I no longer needed to go outside. And I think that's why I felt when I

60
00:03:50,399 --> 00:03:57,165
saw Stranger Things, I was like, oh my God, all of those people are me. It was just absolutely

61
00:03:57,225 --> 00:03:57,745
incredible.

62
00:03:58,726 --> 00:04:04,429
So, I gravitate toward Rolemaster by the time I'm around 14, and I end up rewriting the

63
00:04:04,469 --> 00:04:08,611
rules for encumbrance, which to me looked like this, but actually weren't this.

64
00:04:09,872 --> 00:04:13,854
It ended up being that I had to rewrite the entire thing, which I did, and we played it

65
00:04:13,894 --> 00:04:14,894
for a couple of years.

66
00:04:15,973 --> 00:04:20,095
So in 1981, in a location that at least looked like this,

67
00:04:20,675 --> 00:04:23,016
I got my job at SirTech Software.

68
00:04:23,577 --> 00:04:25,777
I happened to meet another person who worked there.

69
00:04:26,118 --> 00:04:28,999
They were looking for somebody to man the helplines

70
00:04:29,079 --> 00:04:31,380
when this is prior to the internet.

71
00:04:31,420 --> 00:04:34,181
So I memorized a game.

72
00:04:34,221 --> 00:04:35,982
When people called, I would answer the questions

73
00:04:36,002 --> 00:04:37,122
that they had about that game.

74
00:04:38,060 --> 00:04:41,062
So that's how I got into the industry and just worked my way up from there.

75
00:04:41,603 --> 00:04:46,207
The first game I worked on was Wizardry 1, Proving Grounds of the Mad Overlord,

76
00:04:46,267 --> 00:04:53,013
and there is a screenshot of it now. And my mom, she was incredibly proud of me. She felt like I

77
00:04:53,053 --> 00:04:56,937
was really on the cusp of technology, and it certainly wasn't something we could afford,

78
00:04:57,357 --> 00:05:01,340
and it gave me such a head start. It's also where I met my first husband.

79
00:05:01,761 --> 00:05:04,623
We fell deeply in love, and I still, we're still together.

80
00:05:04,904 --> 00:05:06,365
We're still together to this day.

81
00:05:07,326 --> 00:05:08,967
So just again, it was 1981.

82
00:05:09,108 --> 00:05:11,830
I couldn't get enough of computers.

83
00:05:12,090 --> 00:05:13,812
And really working at this company

84
00:05:13,892 --> 00:05:16,695
gave me an opportunity I would not have had access to.

85
00:05:17,095 --> 00:05:19,537
What it also gave me a chance to see was code.

86
00:05:20,658 --> 00:05:24,761
So the first code I actually saw would have been assembly language there,

87
00:05:24,901 --> 00:05:28,824
but I fell head first into Basic,

88
00:05:28,984 --> 00:05:30,445
which I was taking at high school.

89
00:05:30,786 --> 00:05:35,349
So for me, code felt and still feels like Legos.

90
00:05:35,429 --> 00:05:36,850
It feels like digital Legos.

91
00:05:37,230 --> 00:05:41,533
Whatever you understand, you can build something with whatever knowledge you have.

92
00:05:42,074 --> 00:05:46,337
So I begged our high school to continue to offer coding classes, which I took.

93
00:05:46,717 --> 00:05:50,400
And then unbelievably, I left early because I did get that gig at Surtec.

94
00:05:51,600 --> 00:05:54,082
And during that time, we put out a lot of games.

95
00:05:54,422 --> 00:05:58,305
And I continued to work for Surtec as I put myself through college.

96
00:05:58,945 --> 00:06:03,349
So during this time, I never saw myself as a woman in a man's world.

97
00:06:03,449 --> 00:06:06,130
In fact, my world at the time was mostly women.

98
00:06:06,771 --> 00:06:08,972
So this picture, Surtec.

99
00:06:09,840 --> 00:06:12,624
You can see here that there are four women and five men.

100
00:06:12,784 --> 00:06:15,188
I join just after this picture is taken.

101
00:06:15,609 --> 00:06:17,953
And so it was parody, and it felt normal to me.

102
00:06:18,473 --> 00:06:21,638
So if we fast forward many years, up until 2015,

103
00:06:22,179 --> 00:06:23,441
I'm now teaching at a college.

104
00:06:24,850 --> 00:06:27,313
And so I've been in the game industry for 30 years.

105
00:06:27,353 --> 00:06:28,995
I'm also teaching, 30 years, actually,

106
00:06:29,015 --> 00:06:30,377
I've been in the game industry longer than that,

107
00:06:30,417 --> 00:06:33,401
but at this point in time, it's 30 years ahead

108
00:06:33,541 --> 00:06:35,543
and I'm making games, but I'm also teaching.

109
00:06:35,683 --> 00:06:37,386
And as a woman in the university,

110
00:06:37,566 --> 00:06:40,449
I am put in charge of their diversity initiative.

111
00:06:41,310 --> 00:06:46,715
So I actually thought this was a pretty great initiative. It asked us to look at lots of

112
00:06:46,755 --> 00:06:54,201
different things that might impede making a more diverse candidate pool, more diverse PhD applicant

113
00:06:54,241 --> 00:07:00,166
pool. So I was actually pretty excited about it. And it asked us to look at challenges people face.

114
00:07:01,126 --> 00:07:05,749
So, you know, for instance, you know, during childbearing years, access to nursing, sometimes

115
00:07:05,789 --> 00:07:07,210
no maternity policy.

116
00:07:07,971 --> 00:07:11,173
So anyway, I put all this together and I was super charged up to do this.

117
00:07:11,493 --> 00:07:16,696
The first email I get back has the following word in it, that this is half-baked populist

118
00:07:16,776 --> 00:07:17,197
jargon.

119
00:07:18,177 --> 00:07:21,619
And that research into diverse teams and diversity was just...

120
00:07:22,240 --> 00:07:28,362
whatever. And further, the nutshell of it was that women just were not interested in tech,

121
00:07:28,402 --> 00:07:34,924
and there really was nothing you could do to make women interested. So needless to say,

122
00:07:34,944 --> 00:07:42,186
this caught me by massive surprise. And so I decided to ask a question about this.

123
00:07:43,142 --> 00:07:45,983
So I forwarded this email to the head of department

124
00:07:46,023 --> 00:07:48,704
and I said, you know, like I'm offended by this.

125
00:07:49,325 --> 00:07:51,806
It's, this doesn't seem to make any sense.

126
00:07:52,486 --> 00:07:54,987
And the response that I got was this,

127
00:07:55,027 --> 00:07:56,028
this is a direct quote.

128
00:07:56,068 --> 00:07:57,989
There's little point in taking offense.

129
00:07:58,709 --> 00:08:01,210
In fact, if anything, I wasn't taking enough offense.

130
00:08:01,550 --> 00:08:03,671
And so I set out to prove them wrong.

131
00:08:04,372 --> 00:08:07,153
The fact that women have no interest in technology

132
00:08:07,233 --> 00:08:09,294
and have never really had any interest in tech.

133
00:08:10,744 --> 00:08:14,909
So now this moves into the next story, which is archaeology.

134
00:08:16,110 --> 00:08:19,153
What you are looking at here are the first computers.

135
00:08:19,474 --> 00:08:23,058
Women literally were the first computers. That's what this job is called.

136
00:08:25,917 --> 00:08:28,459
And programming jobs were advertised to women

137
00:08:28,519 --> 00:08:30,581
specifically because they required

138
00:08:30,921 --> 00:08:32,943
menial, detail-oriented labor.

139
00:08:32,963 --> 00:08:34,885
And those words are from the advertisements.

140
00:08:34,945 --> 00:08:38,028
And at the time, people deemed that women were a perfect fit.

141
00:08:38,528 --> 00:08:41,391
And in fact, up until the late 60s,

142
00:08:41,831 --> 00:08:45,514
IBM in the UK measured code in girl hours.

143
00:08:47,648 --> 00:08:50,329
I'm finding loads of evidence that at one point in time,

144
00:08:50,489 --> 00:08:53,110
here and there, women were definitely not the minority,

145
00:08:53,190 --> 00:08:55,990
and in some cases, were the overwhelming majority.

146
00:08:56,650 --> 00:08:59,791
It was really deemed that the labor perfectly suited women.

147
00:08:59,811 --> 00:09:01,371
And if you can think about it for a second,

148
00:09:01,872 --> 00:09:03,132
think about a typewriter.

149
00:09:03,952 --> 00:09:05,792
This is a heavy machine, and somebody else

150
00:09:05,812 --> 00:09:07,013
will build the heavy machine.

151
00:09:07,053 --> 00:09:09,153
But who types into the heavy machine?

152
00:09:09,213 --> 00:09:11,574
Well, traditionally, that would have been women.

153
00:09:12,654 --> 00:09:16,435
This menial, detail-oriented mindset

154
00:09:17,115 --> 00:09:21,397
was at the time frightened so that this would be a perfect job for women.

155
00:09:21,937 --> 00:09:26,139
We actually see an amazing case in Dundee.

156
00:09:26,159 --> 00:09:27,939
There's a big study done on this as well.

157
00:09:28,340 --> 00:09:31,181
It was primarily women who built the ZX Spectrum,

158
00:09:31,241 --> 00:09:35,923
and this is one of the most important computers in early European coding.

159
00:09:38,104 --> 00:09:42,026
But these women were made to feel just as if they were sort of the assembly line workers,

160
00:09:42,066 --> 00:09:51,730
not really part of this technological movement that truly defined an entire area in many, many genres.

161
00:09:52,270 --> 00:09:57,233
So, same thing, Cray computer women were often the people who were putting these things together as well.

162
00:09:57,973 --> 00:10:00,955
And so at some point in time, putting these things together

163
00:10:01,356 --> 00:10:02,056
isn't enough.

164
00:10:02,116 --> 00:10:04,418
So women need to learn how to code these things.

165
00:10:04,939 --> 00:10:06,060
And how did they code?

166
00:10:06,080 --> 00:10:08,402
Well, they coded it with 6502 assembly.

167
00:10:08,782 --> 00:10:11,124
It was just the language that the computers understood.

168
00:10:11,144 --> 00:10:12,986
And at this time, there's not a lot,

169
00:10:13,646 --> 00:10:16,509
there's not a tremendous amount of value put onto this, per se.

170
00:10:17,550 --> 00:10:19,892
And what's interesting to me is this

171
00:10:19,952 --> 00:10:22,854
is around the point in time when I am in college.

172
00:10:23,335 --> 00:10:29,257
And I don't remember being the only woman in my college program. In fact, there were loads of women.

173
00:10:30,157 --> 00:10:34,779
There were advertisements in the 70s that actually talked about the computer girls.

174
00:10:34,859 --> 00:10:36,260
A trainee gets 8,000 a year, a girl senior.

175
00:10:38,915 --> 00:10:41,859
Senior systems analyst gets $20,000 up.

176
00:10:42,180 --> 00:10:45,585
And it was really a job that was heavily promoted toward women.

177
00:10:46,246 --> 00:10:48,409
So as the importance of this goes up,

178
00:10:48,590 --> 00:10:51,174
because computers are obviously not going to be a fad,

179
00:10:51,374 --> 00:10:53,738
this is going to keep happening, the pay goes up.

180
00:10:54,572 --> 00:10:57,313
And as the pay goes up, men start to come in.

181
00:10:57,713 --> 00:11:00,895
Now, I'm not saying this to make men go, oh, here we go.

182
00:11:01,035 --> 00:11:03,237
This is the point at which she starts saying

183
00:11:03,277 --> 00:11:04,317
things that make us upset.

184
00:11:04,357 --> 00:11:05,238
No, absolutely not.

185
00:11:05,258 --> 00:11:06,859
I mean, if you are listening to this talk,

186
00:11:07,519 --> 00:11:09,800
I already know that that isn't you.

187
00:11:10,220 --> 00:11:12,942
And in fact, culturally, there were people, in fact,

188
00:11:12,982 --> 00:11:15,623
there were countries where women could not even work if they

189
00:11:15,664 --> 00:11:17,284
were married at this point in time.

190
00:11:17,705 --> 00:11:19,406
Men were the traditional breadwinners,

191
00:11:19,546 --> 00:11:20,946
and therefore, it made sense.

192
00:11:21,347 --> 00:11:26,091
that as the pay is going up, men are going to start coming in looking for that bread that they're hoping to win.

193
00:11:26,131 --> 00:11:27,652
It was just the culture of the time.

194
00:11:28,573 --> 00:11:32,636
And also there was another problem, that as there's more men entering the field,

195
00:11:33,617 --> 00:11:36,419
they didn't necessarily want to be trained by a woman.

196
00:11:38,267 --> 00:11:39,108
Out goes the woman.

197
00:11:39,208 --> 00:11:40,508
It just wasn't going to work.

198
00:11:40,588 --> 00:11:43,110
And so we start seeing a lot of women leave.

199
00:11:43,190 --> 00:11:45,931
Now, culturally, things were not ready

200
00:11:46,691 --> 00:11:48,992
for a women-led tech revolution.

201
00:11:49,052 --> 00:11:50,393
And I think it's helpful to take a look

202
00:11:50,433 --> 00:11:52,114
at the advertisements of the time.

203
00:11:52,654 --> 00:11:53,655
So for instance.

204
00:11:54,536 --> 00:11:59,041
Here's it's a lifesaver. You can get a range by Brown sift with a soil free oven.

205
00:12:00,303 --> 00:12:02,846
And let's take a look at this one. This is from 1974.

206
00:12:02,906 --> 00:12:05,189
And I mind you that we're talking about the same time period. Right.

207
00:12:05,589 --> 00:12:10,455
So just you can see like if these advertisements in just mainstream media were OK.

208
00:12:11,396 --> 00:12:16,538
you know, what would you expect it to look like in other places? So here's another ad from legs in

209
00:12:16,838 --> 00:12:21,820
1970. It's nice to have a girl around the house and I guess step on her head. There's another one

210
00:12:21,840 --> 00:12:26,661
where a husband spanking his wife, or I guess not getting, you know, that she didn't, she didn't

211
00:12:26,721 --> 00:12:30,943
store test their fresh coffee. It's just, it's obviously absolutely ridiculous, but it gives you

212
00:12:30,963 --> 00:12:32,763
an idea of where we're at the time.

213
00:12:33,432 --> 00:12:39,496
So we were really on the verge of a female ed tech revolution, but our culture was not ready for it.

214
00:12:39,516 --> 00:12:40,316
It was a mismatch.

215
00:12:40,917 --> 00:12:44,459
And so this period we're in now could just be an aberration.

216
00:12:44,639 --> 00:12:49,342
And if you're interested in more on this, there is a fantastic book that I highly recommend.

217
00:12:49,702 --> 00:12:51,864
And it's all really well detailed.

218
00:12:52,004 --> 00:12:53,585
It's called Programmed Inequality.

219
00:12:53,625 --> 00:12:55,146
So I encourage you to check that out.

220
00:12:56,046 --> 00:12:58,548
So the next story is the Unicorn Anomaly.

221
00:13:00,658 --> 00:13:03,820
People often view female coders as a bit of an anomaly,

222
00:13:03,960 --> 00:13:07,642
so much so that we actually have the term female coder,

223
00:13:08,342 --> 00:13:09,623
which sounds weird.

224
00:13:09,943 --> 00:13:12,865
And so I sometimes hear questions like this,

225
00:13:12,905 --> 00:13:15,046
like, what's it like to be a female programmer?

226
00:13:15,886 --> 00:13:17,747
what's it like to be a female game designer?

227
00:13:17,827 --> 00:13:19,768
Or what's it like to be a woman in tech?

228
00:13:20,168 --> 00:13:22,589
As if there's one answer to that question.

229
00:13:22,629 --> 00:13:24,690
Like for all of the women watching this,

230
00:13:24,850 --> 00:13:26,590
I'm sure that if we were in a big room,

231
00:13:26,651 --> 00:13:28,011
which we would be, obviously,

232
00:13:28,391 --> 00:13:29,652
but if we were in a big room and I said,

233
00:13:29,692 --> 00:13:32,993
okay, everybody, I'm gonna answer on your behalf.

234
00:13:33,393 --> 00:13:33,974
There's at least.

